========================================
  CHAPTER 15 - FILE MANIPULATION NOTES
========================================

--- WHY USE FILES? ---
- Data stored in variables is TEMPORARY (lost when program ends or variable goes out of scope)
- Files allow LONG-TERM (persistent) data storage
- Data in files exists beyond the duration of program execution

--- FILES & STREAMS ---
- Files are viewed as a sequential stream of bytes
- Every OS has a way to detect End Of File (EOF)
  - EOF is either a marker or a total byte count
- Two types of files:
  1. TEXT files   - every character is two bytes
  2. BINARY files - data stored in raw binary format
- Bit to Byte conversion:
  - 8 bits = 1 byte
  - 1 bit  = 0.125 bytes

--- BINARY FILE SIZES ---
- char   = 2 bytes
- int    = 4 bytes
- double = 8 bytes
- Binary files must be read by programs that understand their specific format/ordering

--- JAVA FILE PACKAGES ---
- java.io         - original file I/O package
- java.nio        - newer, improved file I/O package
- java.util.Formatter - outputs data to any text-based stream (like System.out.printf)
- java.util.Scanner   - reads input from keyboard OR from a file

--- NIO: PATH & PATHS ---
- Path  (interface) - stores a file/directory location
- Paths (class)     - has static method get() to retrieve a Path object
  Example:
    Path path = Paths.get("path/to/dir");

--- NIO: FILES CLASS ---
- Provides static methods for common file/directory operations:
  - Copying files
  - Creating and deleting files and directories
  - Getting file/directory information
  - Reading the contents of files

--- FILE CLASS (java.io.File) ---
- Represents a file or directory path name
- Preferred when performing MORE THAN ONE operation on a file/directory
- Useful File class methods:
  - canRead()          - checks if file is readable
  - canWrite()         - checks if file is writable
  - createNewFile()    - creates a new empty file
  - mkdir()            - creates a new directory
  - delete()           - deletes the file or directory
  - exists()           - checks if the file exists (returns true/false)
  - getName()          - returns the name of the file
  - getAbsolutePath()  - returns the full path of the file
  - length()           - returns the size of the file in bytes
  - list()             - returns a String[] of files and directories

--- READING FROM FILES ---

FileReader:
- Reads characters (NOT bytes) from a file
- Intended for reading TEXT files
- May throw FileNotFoundException
- Always call close() when finished
  Example:
    FileReader fr = new FileReader("input.txt");

BufferedReader:
- Wraps a FileReader for faster, efficient reading
- Reads large blocks of data at once (default: 4 or 8 KB)
- Block reading is much faster for disk access and large files
- Reads characters (text)
- Use readLine() to read one line at a time
  Example:
    BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("input.txt"));
    String line;
    while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
        System.out.println(line);
    }
    br.close();

--- WRITING TO FILES ---

FileWriter:
- Writes characters (NOT bytes) to a file
- Intended for writing TEXT files
- Always call close() when finished
  Example:
    FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("output.txt");
    fw.write("Hello, Java!");
    fw.close();

BufferedWriter:
- Wraps a FileWriter for faster, efficient writing
- Writes large blocks of data at once (default: 4 or 8 KB)
- Block writing is much faster for disk access and large files
- Writes characters (text)
  Example:
    BufferedWriter bw = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter("output.txt"));
    bw.write("Hello, Java!");
    bw.newLine();
    bw.close();

--- QUICK REFERENCE SUMMARY ---

| Class          | Purpose                        | Read/Write |
|----------------|--------------------------------|------------|
| FileReader     | Read text from a file          | Read       |
| BufferedReader | Fast buffered text reading     | Read       |
| FileWriter     | Write text to a file           | Write      |
| BufferedWriter | Fast buffered text writing     | Write      |
| File           | File/directory info & methods  | Both       |
| Scanner        | Read text from file or console | Read       |

--- IMPORTANT REMINDERS ---
- Always close() your readers and writers when done
- Use try-catch blocks to handle IOException and FileNotFoundException
- Buffered classes are faster than non-buffered for large files
- Text files store data as characters; binary files store raw binary data
- Use exists() before reading a file to avoid errors

